# Repo Setup

This document defines the exact structure and intent of every directory in the repository. It exists to prevent confusion and enforce consistent architecture across all stacks.

## Packages

-> core (API): transport and consumer agnostic core logic. Contains the entire business logic and domain layer, no framework bindings. Just raw classes, services. Doesn't know about Next, Express, Fastify or whatever.
-> auth: dedicated authentication API, it uses better-auth internally. It has its own domain complexity (tokens, sessions, providers). The core imports and interacts with it over the wire through well-defined contracts. Core only usage.
-> logger: minimal, dependency-free logging utility for consistent structured logs across packages, never console.log, use the logger from the package.
-> constants: holds shared constants used throughout the repo. Dependency free. Pure JS/TS. These are static values that do not depend on runtime or environment variables. For example, common emails, names, etc.
-> cross-runtime: utilities or services that run identically in Deno, Bun, Node, Cloudflare Workers, or browsers. Used for true cross-environment logic (e.g., universal text formatters).
-> monitor: encapsulates monitoring integrations (Sentry or any other provider). Imported and used by frontends only and core.
-> analytics: integrates tracking providers like PostHog and/or Google Analytics. Imported and used by frontends only and core.
-> db: handles database connections and migrations only. Contains schema definitions and migration scripts. Only imported and used by core. Never any other package or app.
-> seeder: imports the database module and seeds data deterministically for tests or local dev. Never imorted or used, it's simply ran through the CLI locally.
-> env: provides typesafe agnostic environment variable validation (using Zod), ensuring all runtime configs are correct at startup for all apps and packages. Only import and use env vars from this package. Never decalre package level env vars.
-> security: provides cryptographic and security utilities such as hashing, masking, encryption and timing-safe operations. The implementation is hidden. The package is imported and used by core. Never any other package or app.
-> seo: provides reusable helpers to improve SEO handling for server-rendered apps.
-> storage: abstracts blob storage logic. The provider is interchangeable (R2, S3, etc) via an adapter pattern. The methods and the services never change. Imported and use by core. Never any other package or app.
-> design: contains the full design system. All primitive UI components (buttons, inputs, etc) live here. Careful changes here.
-> components: contains higher-level UI components shared across apps, usually for branding purposes mostly, such as headers and footers. Does not hold primitives or app-specific UI. Rarely extended beyond essentials.
-> payments: payments infrastructure. Provider agnostic (Whop, Stripe) with a unified API. Imported and used by core only. 
-> email: email infrastructure, imported and used by core only. Provider agnostic (Resend, Sendgrid), same API.

## Apps

-> www, app, dashboard, mobile, etc: every app directly calls the API layer. No backend, just UI that depends on the same transport abstraction to call the API.
-> api:  The API is a standalone package composed of two distinct sections: the framework plumbing (Next.js, Fastify, Express) and a thin API implementation layer. This package acts as the deployment unit and the RPC bridge, shielding the frontend from the underlying core logic. Frontend apps never call the core directly; instead, they install the API as a simple package and interact with it through a protocol-agnostic bridge. The framework handles the low-level transport while the API layer manages the specific query implementations and boundary definitions. This setup allows the frontend to consume exposed types and call functionality immediately without knowing which tools power the backend. Ultimately, the API serves as a thin, deployable wrapper that transforms internal core logic into a consumer-ready interface.

## Tooling

All tooling packages exist as single sources of truth for configurations used across all packages.
-> eslint: shared ESLint configuration and plugins.
-> playwright: shared Playwright configuration for integration or E2E testing.
-> prettier: Prettier configuration shared across the repo.
-> next: shared Next.js configuration and plugins.
-> typescript: shared tsconfig presets.
-> vitest: shared Vitest configuration for all unit and integration tests.
